This paper discusses the evaluation of semantic properties of word embeddings, which is a common topic in natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML). The paper specifically focuses on the biomedical domain, which suggests a potential fit with the sub-category of computational biology (q-bio.CB) or medical informatics (cs.HC). However, the paper's emphasis on word embeddings and semantic evaluation suggests a stronger fit with NLP and ML sub-categories. The paper proposes modifications to the standard methodology for analogy completion, which is a common task in NLP and ML evaluation. The paper also presents a new dataset for evaluating linguistic regularities in biomedical embeddings, which is a common approach in NLP and ML research. Based on these factors, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CL (Computation and Language), which focuses on NLP, and cs.LG (Machine Learning), which focuses on ML. Other possible sub-categories include cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence), which encompasses both NLP and ML, cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which focuses on neural networks commonly used in NLP and ML, and cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), which also uses embeddings and semantic evaluation techniques.
